<br />
That's true, but since I'm convinced the 3-person Prowler is much less efficient than the 2-person version anyway, I don't see this as an advantage.  Rather the reverse -- little "extra reasons" like this only serve to make people more likely to try to use it, which would be bad.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>oaksilencer wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">that is why nothing can ever be in balance... stats on paper are not real battle situations, real battle situations are unpredictable.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
To say those types of things is to imply that there can be other variables that come into play other than raw statistics (which I would agree with).  However, I'm going to give a straightforward statistical example and offer a question of what type of factors, tangible or intangible, that I'm missing in this particular case.
<br />

<br />
The Magrider has 3500 armor and deals 215 damage per second (assuming the driver's gun isn't being used).  Since it has a crew of two people, we could halve its stats in a hypothetical sort of way and get a feel for what "one person's worth" of Magrider is.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">"One person's worth" of Magrider:</span>
<br />
Offense:  107.5 damage/second vs. vehicles, no damage degradation, explosive shots.
<br />
Defense:  1750 armor.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">"One person's worth" of Prowler machine gun:</span>
<br />
Offense:  120 damage/second vs. vehicles, damage degrades, non-explosive shots.
<br />
Defense:  0 armor.
<br />

<br />
So offensively, things are at best pretty even.  I actually would still prefer the Mag, since the raw damage output would almost always be at least as good owing to the lack of damage degradation, and explosive rounds help a lot against infantry.  It also features slower firing time between shots (one-second "snipes" instead of constant spraying).  Admittedly, the Rail Beam does have that jittery feature and the Prowler 15mm can swivel faster, but it also has those annoying dual crosshairs.
<br />

<br />
Defensively, the Mag winds hands down.  It gets 1750 free armor for its crew member.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">The guns fire in the exact same manner</span> (no arc, extremely fast projectiles).  So what hidden gameplay variable am I missing here?  How could I help but conclude that a person in a Prowler machine gun is far less efficient than a person in a Magrider?
<br />

<br />
Sorry to hijack my own thread from the subject of the lead dev not knowing the nuts and bolts of his own game.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
